WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Welcome back, everyone, to the Data Science Hangout.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:15.000
My name is Randy Zwich.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.000
I'm Senior Director of Developer Relations here at Posit.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.000
I'm filling in for Rachel, as Curtis mentioned.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
And of course, we're happy to have all of you here joining us today.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:34.000
The Hangout is our open space to hear what's going on in the world of data across different industries,

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:41.000
to chat about data science leadership, and connect with others facing similar issues as yourselves.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:47.000
We get together here every Thursday at the same time, same Zoom link.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
And if you're watching this recording and want to join us in the future,

00:00:51.000 --> 00:01:00.000
the YouTube link will have the details below to give you the ability to add it to your calendars.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Please keep in mind we're dedicated to keeping this a friendly and welcoming space for everyone.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:06.000
And we love hearing from you.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
So no matter how many years of experience you have, your title, your industry, programming languages you work in,

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:19.000
or any other differentiator, we want this to be a welcome space for everybody.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.000
And with that, today's Hangout is dedicated to all things Posit Conf 2024.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:33.000
And so we're going to cover questions from workshops to talks to advice for first timers and anything else that's top of mind for you.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.000
And of course, we hope to see many of you at the conference this August in Seattle.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Whether you're joining us in person or virtually, it will be my first Posit Conf.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:52.000
I'm sure there's many others that have, you know, more experience than myself.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And we know that people really enjoy connecting with other Hangout attendees.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And so we want to encourage you to briefly introduce yourself, say hi in the chat, possibly include your role, where you're based.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:16.000
And if you're going to join us in person in Seattle, definitely, you know, add that as well so that you can connect with others, you know, ahead of time.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
There's three main ways that you can jump in and ask questions or share your experiences.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:30.000
One, you know, raise your hand on Zoom and I'll just call in, call on you to read your question.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:37.000
Ideally, this is the best way, our preferred way so that, you know, more people are interacting.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Secondly, you can put a question in the Zoom chat and feel free to put a star next to it if you want me to read it.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:50.000
You know, in the case that you might not be able, you know, be in a quiet environment and can read it yourself.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And then third, we have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Given the topic today, I don't anticipate a lot of anonymous type questions, but, you know, of course, we do provide that link as well.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
And today I'm joined by four PASA co-hosts.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:14.000
We have Anna, who manages our events and will know a lot about the logistics of PASA Conf.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
We have Curtis, who, of course, is here, you know, nearly every week.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:26.000
We have the ever-present Hadley Wickham, who will answer whatever he will answer.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And then finally, we have Isabella, again, who's also a regular at the Data Science Hangout.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:44.000
And so just to kick things off, for my four co-hosts, I would say, you know, what is everybody the most excited about this year?

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:49.000
And I'll call on Isabella first.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Oh, yeah.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
Well, I'm very excited for the conference to be in Seattle.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.000
I used to live in Seattle, and it's absolutely gorgeous in August.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Of course, I'm also looking forward to the talks and the networking opportunities that we'll be able to have in that gorgeous Seattle weather.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:08.000
How about you, Hadley?

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
What are you looking forward to the most?

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Compared to last year, I'm excited that we have Windows.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
That is going to be a big plus to have daylight.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:33.000
I mean, like every year, I'm excited that we just have such an awesome group of speakers who are, like, already starting to get to work on their talks.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:47.000
And I think the other thing that I'm excited about this year is that we are finally communicating the program committee's vision for the talks, which is that there are, like, four talks in a session.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
And we really highly recommend that you stay there for the whole session.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:07.000
And there is no time in the schedule to get from one room to another, which has caused confusion for folks in the past because we failed to, like, accurately help people understand that.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:16.000
So I think in general, I'm excited that we're doing a lot more this year just to give everyone kind of a big picture view of the program.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
So it should be easier to navigate and find what you're looking for.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Okay.

