00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:13.000
Support the speakers. That's always a great one. Be a nodder in the crowd. Okay.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:22.000
Dominic looks like he's going to be traveling all the way from Croatia, so we will have a little extra coffee for Dominic.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:36.000
Oh yeah, and if you're coming from another country, be aware that like it's going to be cold inside because hotels in the US are always set at like 68 degrees.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:53.000
And it's like weather. There's like nothing you can do about it except dress for the conditions, so regardless of what temperature it's going to be in Seattle, like make sure you bring like a warm jacket or throw something to stay cozy in the hotel.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
Okay.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:05.000
I have one other one. I saw the Pac-Man rule. We do that a posit. I think that might be Hadley's favorites thing if you want to go into that a little bit.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:16.000
Yeah, I mean, one of the goals of our goals for comp is just to make it like as welcoming and inclusive as possible, so I know lots of people come.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:26.000
It might be like the only user of the organization, although now we're starting to see companies bring a bunch of people, which is also very cool.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:49.000
But we also know, by and large, it's kind of an introverted crowd at comp, so the Pac-Man rule is just like whenever you're standing in a group of people, make sure to leave like Pac-Man's mouth open so other new people can join, so we want to, you know, make it as easy as possible for you to like walk up and say hi to folks.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:12:08.000
And I think hopefully this year we'll do the birds of a feather pins as well, so just things you can like add to your lanyard topics you're interested in, so when you're like, someone might be a stranger, but if they're interested in the same things as you, that's a great conversation starter.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.000
We have a question from the chat.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:23.000
This is probably Hadley, but open to any of the positive employees. When you're putting a program together, how do you get a feel for what the hot topics are that you want to include?

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:38.000
That's a good question. I think, you know, like a lot of it is driven by just who submits, because that tends to be kind of fairly well correlated with like what people are thinking about.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:56.000
I think like this year, obviously, the kind of hot topic is like generative AI and LLMs, so we're going to, you know, they came up a bunch of times, we're going to have a keynote speaker specifically about that, but I know it's going to come up in other keynote talks as well.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:15.000
So I think it's just like, you know, one of the things that we're like hearing about in the community from our customers, you know, and calls like this, Rachel's on the program committee, so she does a great job of kind of making sure we're thinking about the stuff that you all are thinking about and worrying about.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:35.000
Yeah, but it's tough. It's tough. That's like a big part, like a big part of the challenge is going, you know, taking all 300 something submissions, getting them scored, and then like starting to form a cohesive program out of them to try and get some order from the chaos.

